{
  "doc_id": "14886",
  "text": "Nitric oxide is another radical that can be produced by enzymatic and non-enzymatic reactions in the biological systems [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Despite its radical nature, NOÁ may have antioxidant properties [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The antioxidant properties of NOÁ can be also inferred by recent intriguing experimental models introduced by the group of Roberto Bolli. They used a mouse model of cardiomyocyterestricted overexpression of extracellular superoxide dismutase (ecSOD) [CITATION_5] and a model with inducible NOS (iNOS) gene transfer [CITATION_6] . In the model with cardiacspecific ecSOD overexpression, they observed an attenuated levels of ROS which was attributed to increased NOÁ availability in response to I/R leading to protection against reperfusion injury [CITATION_7] . In the model with iNOS gene transfer, they observed long-term (1 year) cardioprotection against I/R injury, without negative functional consequences [CITATION_8] . However caution must be used in the interpretation and translation to the clinic of this approach. In fact, iNOS expression in peripheral blood cells may mediate myocardial I/R injury [CITATION_9] .",
